# Coding Conventions (temporal_filtering)

## 1. Schema is the single source of truth
- Model parameters MUST be defined in a schema (`ADAPTIVE_SCHEMA`, `CONDUCTANCE_SCHEMA`).
  `assign / bounds / guess / nparams / tables` all derive from the schema.
- NO scattered hardcoded indices (`z[130:135]`, `z[135]`). Changing a parameter
  happens in ONE place: the schema.

## 2. Core must be flexible for new parameters
- Core (`fc`) must accept new params (e.g. `out_scale`, 1 global or 65 per-cell) by
  adding ONE schema segment — without editing `calc_cost` / `do_many_runs` / table logic.

## 3. Reuse, never re-implement
- Test/experiment scripts MUST `import run` / `import fc` and reuse existing functions.
- NEVER re-implement the model forward / trainer / cost in a test.
- NEVER duplicate an existing function (e.g. don't wrap your own `out_dir` over `run.run_dir`).

## 4. Tests follow the run.py pipeline EXACTLY
- Every trained variant calls `run.run_training(...)` and gets its OWN `run_<id>` folder.
- Each folder must contain the FULL run.py output set: `*.npy`, `_costs.npy`,
  `_table.csv`, `cost_curve.png`, `model_vs_data.png`, `model_all_cells.png`,
  `best_param.npy`, `model_type.txt`. Never save only a subset.
- Use run.py's naming. Do NOT invent names (no `results.txt`, no `*_outscale_table.csv`).

## 5. run.py stays minimal
- `run.py` holds only verified, general functions. Do NOT add test-only code to it.

## 6. Clean output dir
- Output dir contains ONLY `adaptive/` and `conductance/` — no `test/` subdir.
- No junk files (`runs_summary.csv`, `globals.csv` are banned).
- CSVs must be strictly rectangular (uniform columns, no comment/blank/ragged lines);
  fold global scalars into the table as constant columns.

## 7. Claims need experimental evidence
- Do not assert behavior (e.g. "scale makes it stable") without an experiment + data.
  Never conclude from a single loss number.

## 8. Naming
- Use clear, meaningful names. No vague/ad-hoc names.
